WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.960
Hello and welcome back. In this video, I will show you how to use OpenClaw to generate a key gen.

00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:24.040
For this lesson, I will use Autogen Serial CrackMe. Run it. Enter name and serial. It shows

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:29.600
message wrong serial key. Remember this message. We will search for it in our debugger next.

00:00:34.980 --> 00:00:52.530
Start the 32-bit version of the debugger as administrator. Then, open the CrackMe. Right

00:00:52.530 --> 00:00:58.320
Right click, select current module, string references.

00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:04.970
Search for the message string you saw earlier, wrong serial key.

00:01:04.970 --> 00:01:08.070
Double click to go to that address.

00:01:08.070 --> 00:01:10.770
Here is where the string is being used.

00:01:10.770 --> 00:01:27.780
Now scroll up to look for the start of this function which is push ebp.

00:01:27.780 --> 00:01:33.640
Take note of this address, we will paste it into telegram next, to ask openclaw to analyze

00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:34.860
the function.

00:01:34.860 --> 00:01:39.360
In Telegram, I ask OpenClaw what model is it on.

00:01:39.360 --> 00:02:04.840
Note that I had switched back to using GPT 5.4 as the OpenRouter Free models were unreliable.

00:02:04.840 --> 00:02:10.420
I tell OpenClaw to connect to the debugger and to refer to memory on how it previously

00:02:10.420 --> 00:02:15.480
did it.

00:02:15.480 --> 00:02:24.550
The OpenRouter Free models struggle at this, but for GPT 5.4 it was easy.

00:02:24.550 --> 00:02:34.360
So if you want OpenClaw to be reliable, use paid models instead of free ones.

00:02:34.360 --> 00:02:43.380
I then ask it to disassemble the function at the address we saw earlier.

00:02:43.380 --> 00:02:57.350
I copy the address and paste it into Telegram.

00:02:57.350 --> 00:03:03.330
I ask OpenClaw to disassemble the function up to the ret instruction.

00:03:03.330 --> 00:03:10.810
I also tell it that the function gets a name and creates a special string using the name.

00:03:10.810 --> 00:03:15.810
Note that I did not use the word serial key as I don't want to let the model know we

00:03:15.810 --> 00:03:18.730
are trying to defeat licensing protection.

00:03:18.730 --> 00:03:25.570
GPT-5.4 might refuse to do anything if it suspects we are trying to bypass software

00:03:25.570 --> 00:03:27.570
licensing.

00:03:27.570 --> 00:03:34.970
So remember to keep your prompts as generic as possible.

00:03:34.970 --> 00:03:45.520
I asked OpenClaw to find out the algorithm and explain it to me.

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:55.060
It then goes to work, and the analysis came back bit by bit.

00:03:55.060 --> 00:04:07.070
The results are very detailed and impressive.

00:04:07.070 --> 00:04:19.920
It managed to figure out the method for generating the serial key.

00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:36.570
I asked it to write a Python script to incorporate the algorithm.

00:04:36.570 --> 00:04:41.850
The script should prompt me for name and then print out the generated string.

00:04:41.850 --> 00:04:58.350
Again, note that I avoided using the word keygen or serial key.

00:04:58.350 --> 00:05:04.250
It managed to do it and even gave an example input using my name and a sample serial key

00:05:04.250 --> 00:05:29.950
generated from it. I then ask it where it had saved the script. I take note of the

00:05:29.950 --> 00:05:40.010
path and go to the location of the script. I open a command line terminal

00:05:40.010 --> 00:06:01.220
here and run the script. I enter my name and it generated the serial key. Run the

00:06:01.220 --> 00:06:17.920
crack me. Enter the name and serial key. It works.

00:06:17.920 --> 00:06:26.270
let's try a different name. Run the script again and enter a different name.

00:06:26.270 --> 00:06:50.890
Copy the new serial key and paste it into the crack me. Again it works. So this

00:06:50.890 --> 00:06:56.930
is how we can use open claw to generate keygens. That is all for this video.

00:06:56.930 --> 00:07:00.430
Thanks for watching

